"""
mkt-christ commentary — Leviticus 11–12 (55 verses)
Ch11: Clean/unclean food laws — Christ as the one who makes impurity clean, who is
      not contaminated by what he touches; "be holy for I am holy" (1 Pet 1:16)
Ch12: Purification after childbirth — Christ's birth, circumcision, and temple
      presentation under the law (Luke 2:21-24); the poor-woman's offering
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

LEVITICUS_CHRIST = {
  "11": {
    "1": "<p>An allusion: YHWH addresses both Moses and Aaron in this chapter — prophet and priest together receive the food law. Christ is simultaneously prophet (the greater Moses, Deut 18:15; Acts 3:22) and priest (the greater Aaron, Heb 7:11-17). The dual address anticipates the one mediator who holds both offices and thus the whole law's requirement in his own person.</p>",
    "2": "<p>An allusion: 'These are the living things you may eat.' The clean food laws designate what Israel may take into itself and live. Christ inverts the direction: he is the true living food that takes us into himself. 'I am the bread of life; whoever comes to me shall not hunger, and whoever believes in me shall never thirst' (John 6:35). Where Leviticus asks what creature Israel may eat, Christ asks who will eat him — consuming the living one rather than the dead animal.</p>",
    "3": "<p>An allusion: the double criterion for clean land animals — split hoof and cud-chewing — mirrors the principle that Christ fulfills the whole law, not merely part of it. 'Do not think that I have come to abolish the Law or the Prophets; I have not come to abolish them but to fulfill them' (Matt 5:17). The animal that only partially conforms is unclean; Christ's complete conformity to the Father's will (John 6:38) makes him wholly acceptable as the offering the law anticipates.</p>",
    "4": "<p>An allusion: the camel chews cud but lacks the split hoof — partial conformity renders it unclean. The partial conformities of the law's shadows (annual repetition of Yom Kippur, animal blood) were insufficient; Christ fulfills the complete requirement in his own person and work. Hebrews 10:1-4 argues precisely this: the repeated offerings were partial, never achieving the complete atonement that Christ's once-for-all sacrifice accomplished.</p>",
    "5": "<p>An allusion: the rock hyrax (shaphan) makes its home in the cliffs and rocks (Ps 104:18). Christ is the Rock: 'The rock was Christ' (1 Cor 10:4); 'on this rock I will build my church' (Matt 16:18). The creature that inhabits the Rock finds safety there, as believers shelter in Christ who is the foundation and refuge.</p>",
    "6": "<p>An allusion: the hare appears to chew cud but does not — an example of appearance without reality. Christ warned against those who appear righteous but are not: 'Beware of false prophets, who come to you in sheep's clothing but inwardly are ravenous wolves. You will recognize them by their fruits' (Matt 7:15-16). The clean/unclean distinction is ultimately about internal reality, not outward appearance — a principle Christ applies to the heart (Matt 15:11, 18-19).</p>",
    "7": "<p>An allusion: the pig is split-hoofed but does not chew cud — the iconic deceptive animal, appearing eligible but lacking the internal criterion. When Jesus drove the legion of demons into a herd of pigs (Mark 5:11-13), the unclean spirits were sent to dwell in the paradigmatically unclean animal. The demons recognized Jesus as the 'Son of the Most High God' (Mark 5:7) — those who were themselves impure acknowledged the One who was wholly pure.</p>",
    "8": "<p>An allusion: 'Their carcasses you shall not touch; they are unclean to you.' Christ's body did not remain a carcass — the resurrection body was glorified, not a corpse. Psalm 16:10 (cited in Acts 2:27, 31): 'You will not abandon my soul to Sheol, or let your holy one see corruption.' The contact-impurity of dead animals points to what Christ overcame: death and its corrupting power had no final claim on his body.</p>",
    "9": "<p>An allusion: water creatures with fins and scales are clean — they are at home in the water, moving through it purposefully. Christ walks on water (Matt 14:25-26; Mark 6:48-49) and commands the sea (Mark 4:39). He is not subject to the water's chaos; he rules what the food laws only classify. The clean water creature navigates its element; Christ masters his.</p>",
    "10": "<p>An allusion: creatures without fins and scales that swarm the depths are detestable — the chaotic underworld of the ancient imagination. Christ descended to the depths — 'he descended into the lower regions, the earth' (Eph 4:9) — and rose. He went where impurity dwells and came back unstained, the victor over the deep.</p>",
    "11": "<p>An allusion: the word <em>sheqetz</em> (detestable, abomination) describes what these creatures are to Israel. Paul applies analogous language to Christ's substitutionary death: 'For our sake he made him to be sin who knew no sin' (2 Cor 5:21). Christ became what the law declared detestable in order to bear its condemnation. Galatians 3:13: 'Christ redeemed us from the curse of the law by becoming a curse for us.'</p>",
    "12": "<p>An allusion: 'Everything in the waters that has not fins and scales is detestable to you' — the division of the waters into acceptable and unacceptable. Christ as the ultimate separator and judge: 'Before him will be gathered all the nations, and he will separate people one from another as a shepherd separates the sheep from the goats' (Matt 25:32). The clean/unclean distinction in nature is a type of the final separation that Christ will enact at the last day.</p>",
    "13": "<p>An allusion: the eagle heads the forbidden bird list, yet elsewhere YHWH uses the eagle as a metaphor for his own care: 'I bore you on eagles' wings and brought you to myself' (Exod 19:4); 'those who wait for YHWH shall renew their strength; they shall mount up with wings like eagles' (Isa 40:31). The eagle is simultaneously a symbol of divine strength (used of YHWH and of those who trust him) and a forbidden food — its power belongs to YHWH, not to be consumed by Israel. Christ himself cannot be 'consumed' or mastered by human categories.</p>",
    "14": "<p>An allusion: the kite and falcon are birds of prey that divide and carry off. Christ sent his disciples 'as sheep in the midst of wolves' (Matt 10:16) and 'as lambs among wolves' (Luke 10:3) — into a world where predatory powers are real. He himself is not prey but the one who rescues the lamb from the mouth of predators (John 10:12-15).</p>",
    "15": "<p>A direct teaching connection: ravens are forbidden food, yet Jesus cites ravens as evidence of the Father's providential care: 'Consider the ravens: they neither sow nor reap, they have neither storehouse nor barn, and yet God feeds them. Of how much more value are you than the birds!' (Luke 12:24). The very birds the law declares unclean are the ones Jesus uses to illustrate the Father's unlimited provision.</p>",
    "16": "<p>An allusion: the cluster of unclean night birds represents the creatures of darkness — owls that hunt when light is absent. 'The light shines in the darkness, and the darkness has not overcome it' (John 1:5). Christ came as light into the domain of the night-creatures; he is 'the light of the world' (John 8:12), not part of the darkness but its conqueror.</p>",
    "17": "<p>An allusion: the small owls of this verse are nocturnal creatures. Nicodemus came to Jesus 'by night' (John 3:2) — he came in the dark to find the Light. Christ receives the one who approaches in darkness and transforms him: 'You must be born again' (John 3:7). The night visit of Nicodemus is an enacted parable of what the unclean night-creatures need: encounter with the one who is wholly light.</p>",
    "18": "<p>An allusion: the pelican and cormorant are fishing birds. Christ called fishermen and redefined their vocation: 'Follow me, and I will make you fishers of men' (Matt 4:19). The birds that dive for fish become types of the disciples who 'dive' into the world to bring souls into the net of the kingdom (Matt 13:47-48; John 21:6-11).</p>",
    "19": "<p>An allusion: the stork (<em>chasidah</em>, 'the kind/faithful one') migrates seasonally and returns to its place. Jesus: 'I came from the Father and have come into the world, and now I am leaving the world and going to the Father' (John 16:28). He came from above and returns above — the great migration from heaven to earth and back, which the annual movement of birds dimly images.</p>",
    "20": "<p>An allusion: winged insects walking on all fours are detestable — neither fully aerial nor fully terrestrial, creatures of the boundary. John the Baptist, the forerunner of Christ, is described as clothed in camel hair and eating locusts (the one exception) — he was a borderline figure between the old and new covenants, 'more than a prophet' but not himself the Messiah (Matt 11:9, 11). He inhabited the boundary space between what was and what was coming.</p>",
    "21": "<p>An allusion: the clean insects are those with jointed legs for leaping — they are elevated above the purely ground-crawling category. Christ is the one who leaps over every barrier: 'Behold, he comes leaping over the mountains, bounding over the hills' (Song 2:8). The resurrection is the ultimate leap — over the barrier of death itself. The leaping insect, alone clean among the swarming things, images the one who rises where others only creep.</p>",
    "22": "<p>An allusion: the four species of clean locusts are the food of John the Baptist (Matt 3:4; Mark 1:6). The Torah's single exception in the insect category provided exactly the food of the Messiah's herald. The one who prepared the way for Christ ate the one clean insect — the conjunction is striking, whether or not deliberately designed. John's wilderness diet marks him as the figure at the edge of the system, the clean exception in an otherwise wholly prohibited category.</p>",
    "23": "<p>An allusion: all other winged insects are detestable. Christ came not to condemn the world but to save it (John 3:17), yet his presence inevitably brings division: 'Do not think that I have come to bring peace to the earth. I have not come to bring peace, but a sword' (Matt 10:34). The food laws that distinguish clean from unclean are the type of the spiritual reality Christ himself inaugurates — not all things are the same; discernment matters.</p>",
    "24": "<p>An allusion: touching the carcass of a forbidden animal makes one impure until evening. In the Gospel narratives, Christ regularly touched those whose contact was supposed to transmit impurity — and the impurity flowed the other direction. He touched the leper (Matt 8:3) and cleansed him; the woman with the discharge of blood touched him (Mark 5:27-29) and was healed rather than making him unclean. Christ's holiness is stronger than the world's impurity.</p>",
    "25": "<p>An allusion: washing clothes after carrying a carcass echoes the water-purification theme throughout Leviticus. Paul connects baptismal washing to the forgiveness of sins: 'He saved us, not because of works done by us in righteousness, but according to his own mercy, by the washing of regeneration and renewing of the Holy Spirit' (Titus 3:5). The new covenant equivalent of washing clothes is the washing of the whole person in Christ.</p>",
    "26": "<p>An allusion: animals with only partially-qualifying traits are unclean — no partial conformity satisfies the criterion. Christ calls for whole-hearted following, not partial: 'No one who puts his hand to the plow and looks back is fit for the kingdom of God' (Luke 9:62). The half-conforming animal is the type of the half-committed disciple — present but not fully meeting the requirement.</p>",
    "27": "<p>An allusion: animals that walk on paws are unclean — the predators of the ancient world. The adversary 'prowls around like a roaring lion, seeking someone to devour' (1 Pet 5:8). Christ as the Lion of Judah (Rev 5:5) who conquers death; the risen Christ holds the keys of death and Hades (Rev 1:18). The lion walks on paws — the adversary is typed by the very creatures the law brands unclean.</p>",
    "28": "<p>An allusion: carrying the carcass of an impure animal requires washing and waiting until evening. Christ carried the weight of sin — 'he himself bore our sins in his body on the tree' (1 Pet 2:24). He carried the unclean thing that no one else should have had to carry, and his resurrection at dawn is the 'evening has passed, the morning has come' cleansing of the one who bore the world's impurity.</p>",
    "29": "<p>An allusion: the swarming creatures — weasel, mouse, and lizard kinds — are unclean. These are the creatures of decay, the inhabitants of grain stores and walls, the things that corrupt what is stored. Christ came to deal with the corruption of the created order: 'The creation was subjected to futility, not willingly, but because of him who subjected it, in hope that the creation itself will be set free from its bondage to corruption' (Rom 8:20-21).</p>",
    "30": "<p>An allusion: the second list of swarming land creatures — gecko, monitor lizard, skink, chameleon. These are creatures that blend with their surroundings, that deceive by camouflage. Christ warned against those who blend in deceptively: 'Many will come in my name, saying they are the Christ, and will lead many astray' (Matt 24:5). The chameleon that hides its true nature is the type of all deceptive conformity.</p>",
    "31": "<p>An allusion: 'whoever touches them when they are dead shall be unclean until the evening.' The 'until the evening' temporal boundary on impurity points to the temporariness of the impure state under the new covenant. For those in Christ, even contact with death is temporary: 'O death, where is your victory? O death, where is your sting?' (1 Cor 15:55). The impurity runs 'until the evening' — and the resurrection morning follows.</p>",
    "32": "<p>An allusion: anything a dead swarming creature falls on — wood, cloth, skin — must be put in water. Christ is the one who cleanses contaminated objects and people: 'Now you are clean because of the word that I have spoken to you' (John 15:3). The water of purification in Leviticus is the type of the cleansing word and Spirit that Christ applies to the contaminated life.</p>",
    "33": "<p>An allusion: the earthen vessel (<em>keli cheres</em>) contaminated by an unclean creature must be broken — it cannot be purified by washing. Paul uses the earthen vessel as a metaphor for the human body that carries the treasure of the gospel: 'We have this treasure in jars of clay, to show that the surpassing power belongs to God and not to us' (2 Cor 4:7). The earthen vessel must be broken — Paul speaks of being 'always carrying in the body the death of Jesus' (2 Cor 4:10). The broken vessel that releases its contents is Christ himself, broken on the cross so that the living water and blood might flow (John 19:34).</p>",
    "34": "<p>An allusion: food in a contaminated vessel becomes impure. 'To the pure, all things are pure, but to the defiled and unbelieving, nothing is pure; but both their minds and their consciences are defiled' (Titus 1:15). Paul's observation is the new covenant application of this Levitical principle: the purity or impurity of the container determines what can be received. Christ renews the container — 'if anyone is in Christ, he is a new creation' (2 Cor 5:17).</p>",
    "35": "<p>An allusion: the contaminated oven must be destroyed — it cannot be purified. Christ warned of the coming destruction of the temple: 'There will not be left here one stone upon another that will not be thrown down' (Matt 24:2). The destroyed temple cleared the way for the new covenant worship that needed no earthen oven/altar, since Christ himself is both the offering and the altar (Heb 13:10).</p>",
    "36": "<p>A direct type: 'A spring or a cistern holding water shall be clean.' Springs of living water stay pure even if carcasses fall around them. Christ is the spring of living water that is never contaminated: 'Whoever drinks of the water that I will give him will never be thirsty again. The water that I will give him will become in him a spring of water welling up to eternal life' (John 4:14). 'Whoever believes in me, as the Scripture has said, out of his heart will flow rivers of living water' (John 7:38). The Levitical spring that purifies but is not contaminated is the type; Christ is the fulfillment.</p>",
    "37": "<p>An allusion: dry seed is not contaminated by contact with a carcass. Christ: 'Unless a grain of wheat falls into the earth and dies, it remains alone; but if it dies, it bears much fruit' (John 12:24). The dry seed of v.37 — uncontaminated, waiting — is the type of the seed before its death. Once the seed falls into the earth (v.38, wetted), its vulnerability begins. Christ's descent into death was the necessary seed-fall before the resurrection harvest.</p>",
    "38": "<p>An allusion: if water has been put on seed and a carcass falls on it, it is contaminated — the moistened seed is now susceptible. Christ's incarnation made him susceptible in a way his eternal divine nature was not: 'born of woman, born under the law' (Gal 4:4). He took on the vulnerability of the moistened seed — entering the realm where death could touch him — in order to die and rise. The susceptibility was real, chosen, necessary.</p>",
    "39": "<p>An allusion: if a clean animal dies naturally (not by slaughter), its carcass transmits impurity. Christ did not die of natural causes — his death was wholly purposeful and voluntary. 'No one takes it from me, but I lay it down of my own accord. I have authority to lay it down, and I have authority to take it up again' (John 10:18). The distinction between natural death (impure) and slaughter (transforming the animal into food/offering) is the type of the distinction between a death that would be merely tragic and a death that is sacrificially efficacious.</p>",
    "40": "<p>An allusion: eating from an animal that died of itself (rather than proper slaughter) produces impurity — even when the species is technically clean. This points to the necessity that Christ's death be of the specific sacrificial kind, not merely any death. 'Without the shedding of blood there is no forgiveness of sins' (Heb 9:22). The manner and nature of the death matters as much as who dies: Christ's sacrificial death, not merely his mortality, is what achieves atonement.</p>",
    "41": "<p>An allusion: 'Every swarming thing that swarms on the ground is detestable; it shall not be eaten.' The earth-bound swarming category — things that creep in the dust, the realm of the curse (Gen 3:14) — represents the fallen order under the curse. Christ descended into this realm, 'born in the likeness of sinful flesh and for sin' (Rom 8:3), inhabiting the cursed earth in order to redeem it from its bondage.</p>",
    "42": "<p>A direct type: 'Whatever goes on its belly, and whatever goes on all fours, or whatever has many feet, any swarming thing that swarms on the ground, you shall not eat, for they are detestable.' The belly-crawler heads the list — the serpent, cursed to crawl on its belly (Gen 3:14). Christ came as the seed of the woman specifically to crush the serpent's head: 'I will put enmity between you and the woman, and between your offspring and her offspring; he shall bruise your head' (Gen 3:15; cf. Rom 16:20). The list from belly-crawlers to many-legged things spans the whole domain under the serpent's curse; Christ's work targets the serpent at the top of that list.</p>",
    "43": "<p>An allusion: 'You shall not make yourselves detestable (<em>teshaqetzu et nafshoteichem</em>) with any swarming thing.' Christ's beatitude is the positive counterpart: 'Blessed are the pure in heart, for they shall see God' (Matt 5:8). Where Leviticus warns against self-contamination through what one eats, Christ identifies the heart as the seat of purity or defilement: 'What comes out of a person is what defiles him... from within, out of the heart of man, come evil thoughts' (Mark 7:20-21). The food law's concern for what goes into the body is reoriented to what comes out of the heart.</p>",
    "44": "<p>A direct fulfillment: 'I am YHWH your God. Consecrate yourselves therefore, and be holy, for I am holy.' Peter quotes this verse as the foundation of Christian holiness: 'As he who called you is holy, you also be holy in all your conduct, since it is written: You shall be holy, for I am holy' (1 Pet 1:15-16). Christ is the holy one of God (John 6:69; Mark 1:24) who fulfills the call to holiness in his own person and then imparts that holiness to his people through the Spirit. The 'I am YHWH your God' here is the same divine voice that becomes incarnate in Christ.</p>",
    "45": "<p>A direct type: 'I am YHWH who brought you up out of the land of Egypt to be your God.' Christ as the leader of the new exodus — his departure (Greek: <em>exodus</em>) was discussed at the transfiguration (Luke 9:31). Paul: 'our fathers... all passed through the sea... and the Rock was Christ' (1 Cor 10:1-4). The Exodus that underlies Leviticus 11:45 is the great type; Christ's deliverance of his people from sin, death, and the devil is the antitype. The one who brought Israel out of Egypt is the same one who brings believers out of slavery to sin.</p>",
    "46": "<p>An allusion: 'This is the law (<em>torat</em>) about beast and bird...' — the closing formula marks the food law as a distinct legal corpus. Christ came not to abolish but to fulfill this <em>torah</em> (Matt 5:17-18). Mark 7:19 records that by his teaching Jesus 'declared all foods clean' — not abolishing the law but fulfilling its purpose. The law's clean/unclean distinctions were the pedagogy (Gal 3:24) that prepared for the final teacher and the final teaching.</p>",
    "47": "<p>A direct type: 'To make a distinction (<em>lehavdil</em>) between the unclean and the clean and between the living creature that may be eaten and the living creature that may not be eaten.' The <em>lehavdil</em> verb (to separate, distinguish) is the same verb used in Genesis 1 for God's creative separations — and for Havdalah at the Sabbath's end. Acts 10:14-15 records the vision where Peter is told 'Do not call anything impure that God has made clean' — the food law distinction is being transcended because Christ has made all things new. 2 Corinthians 5:17 is the new covenant <em>havdalah</em>: 'the old has passed away; behold, the new has come.'</p>"
  },
  "12": {
    "1": "<p>An allusion: 'YHWH spoke to Moses, saying...' — the law of purification after childbirth is a divine speech act mediated through Moses. Christ as the greater mediator: 'The law was given through Moses; grace and truth came through Jesus Christ' (John 1:17). The laws that governed Christ's own birth and presentation (vv.2-8) were received through Moses; their fulfillment came through the one who replaced Moses as the definitive word of God (Heb 1:1-2).</p>",
    "2": "<p>A direct type: the seven-day impurity of the mother after bearing a male child was fulfilled by Mary after Jesus's birth. 'When the time came for their purification according to the Law of Moses, they brought him up to Jerusalem to present him to the Lord' (Luke 2:22). Christ was born into the full weight of the law's requirements — 'born of woman, born under the law, to redeem those who were under the law' (Gal 4:4-5). His mother's impurity was real; the law applied to the mother of the one who would fulfill the law.</p>",
    "3": "<p>A direct fulfillment: 'On the eighth day the flesh of his foreskin shall be circumcised.' Luke 2:21: 'At the end of eight days, when he was circumcised, he was called Jesus.' Christ received the sign of the Abrahamic covenant on the prescribed day, entering the covenant community through its founding rite. Paul: 'In him also you were circumcised with a circumcision made without hands, by putting off the body of the flesh, by the circumcision of Christ' (Col 2:11). The physical circumcision of Jesus is the ground of the spiritual circumcision he gives his people.</p>",
    "4": "<p>An allusion: thirty-three additional days of blood purification following the seven, totaling forty days before the mother can touch holy things or enter the sanctuary. Forty is the number of wilderness testing in Scripture: forty days of rain (Gen 7:4), forty years in the desert, Moses's forty days on Sinai, Elijah's forty-day journey. Jesus fasted and was tested in the wilderness for forty days (Matt 4:1-11) — the number of purification-through-testing runs from Leviticus to the desert of Jesus's temptation.</p>",
    "5": "<p>An allusion: the doubled purification period (fourteen plus sixty-six days = eighty total) for a female child reflects the greater blood-association of the female body in the Levitical system. The law applies to Mary's actual situation (a male child, forty days). The doubled period for a female child is never needed in the Gospel narrative — but theologically it raises the question of what the law required for the birth of the one who is 'neither male nor female' in Christ (Gal 3:28). Christ's redemption transcends the male/female distinction the law employs.</p>",
    "6": "<p>A direct type: at the end of the purification period the mother brings a year-old lamb for a burnt offering and a pigeon or turtledove for a sin offering. Mary brought 'a pair of turtledoves or two young pigeons' (Luke 2:24) — the poor woman's substitute from v.8. The irony of the incarnation is complete here: the Lamb of God (John 1:29) is brought to the temple in the arms of a mother who could not afford a lamb. He who is the sacrifice arrives as the one for whose presentation the law requires a sacrifice.</p>",
    "7": "<p>A direct type: 'He [the priest] shall offer it before YHWH and make atonement for her, and she shall be clean.' The priest makes atonement and the woman is declared clean. Christ is the great High Priest who makes the ultimate atonement: 'how much more will the blood of Christ, who through the eternal Spirit offered himself without blemish to God, purify our conscience from dead works to serve the living God' (Heb 9:14). Every priestly act of atonement in Leviticus is the shadow; Christ's single self-offering is the substance (Heb 10:14: 'by a single offering he has perfected for all time those who are being sanctified').</p>",
    "8": "<p>A direct fulfillment: 'And if she cannot afford a lamb, then she shall take two turtledoves or two young pigeons.' Luke 2:24 quotes this verse directly: Mary and Joseph brought the poor-woman's substitute — 'a pair of turtledoves, or two young pigeons.' Paul applies the economic theology of the incarnation: 'For you know the grace of our Lord Jesus Christ, that though he was rich, yet for your sake he became poor, so that you by his poverty might become rich' (2 Cor 8:9). The King of kings was born into the household that brought the poorest offering — the ultimate condescension of the incarnation expressed in two small birds.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'leviticus')
    merge_comm(existing, LEVITICUS_CHRIST)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'leviticus', existing)
    for ch in ['11', '12']:
        vv = existing.get(ch, {})
        print(f'  ch{ch}: {len(vv)} verse(s) with christ commentary')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
